ondon before 1915, bringing the material history of its formation into clearer and more detailed focus than ever before. Drawing on a wealth of disciplinary evidence, from socio-economics to histories of sexuality, bohemia, consumerism, politics, and popular culture, David Cottington explores the different models of cultural collectivity in, and presumed hierarchies between, these two focal cities, while identifying points of ideological influence and difference between them. He reveals the avant-garde to be at once complicit with, resistant to, and a product of the modernizing forces of professionalization, challenging the conventional wisdom on this moment of cultural formation and offering the means to reset the terms of avant-garde studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zFrancezParisxHistoryy20th century. 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074977940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030026507140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300265071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300265071/original  a978-3-11-074977-9  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles